{
  "response": "# Complex Modal with Multi-Section Form Accessibility Design Plan\n\n> **For Claude:** Use a11y-planner protocol. Review with a11y-critic after implementation.  \n> **Compliance target:** WCAG 2.2 AA  \n> **Users who need accessibility:** Screen reader users, keyboard-only users, low vision users, switch users, touch users, users with cognitive or motor disabilities  \n> **Assistive technologies:** JAWS, NVDA, VoiceOver, keyboard-only navigation, browser zoom, touch input\n\n**Feature:** A reusable React modal dialog containing a variable-size multi-section e-commerce form with validation, stacked modal support, keyboard focus trap, Escape close behavior, and focus restoration.  \n**Risk Level:** High  \n**Component/Page Type:** Modal dialog + multi-section form + validation flow\n\n---\n\n## Scope & Context\n\nThis plan covers a new reusable modal component for a React e-commerce application. The modal contains a multi-section form with 10+ fields, including text inputs, select controls, checkboxes, and radio groups. Validation occurs on blur and submit. The dialog may be stacked with other dialogs, so focus ownership and restoration must be explicit.\n\nThis plan is not claiming the form\u2019s business validation rules are complete. It only defines how validation state, error recovery, keyboard operation, and screen reader communication must work accessibly.\n\nPrimary accessibility risks:\n\n- Focus escaping to the page behind the modal.\n- Focus not returning to the correct trigger after close.\n- Nested/stacked modals restoring focus to the wrong element.\n- Validation errors appearing visually but not being programmatically associated with fields.\n- Long forms becoming difficult to navigate without fieldsets, legends, headings, and summary behavior.\n- Escape closing the wrong modal when multiple modals are stacked.\n- Touch targets and focus indicators failing WCAG 2.2 AA.\n\n---\n\n## Semantic Structure Plan\n\nThe modal follows the WAI-ARIA APG Modal Dialog pattern:\n\n- APG Modal Dialog Pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/dialog-modal/\n- WCAG: 2.1.1 Keyboard, 2.1.2 No Keyboard Trap, 2.4.3 Focus Order, 2.4.7 Focus Visible, 2.4.11 Focus Not Obscured, 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value\n\nThe modal must render outside the normal page flow, typically through a React portal, while preserving correct accessibility behavior.\n\n### Required Structure\n\n```html\n<body>\n  <button id=\"checkout-modal-trigger\">\n    Open checkout details\n  </button>\n\n  <main id=\"main-content\">\n    Page content behind modal\n  </main>\n\n  <div class=\"modal-layer\">\n    <div class=\"modal-backdrop\"></div>\n\n    <div\n      role=\"dialog\"\n      aria-modal=\"true\"\n      aria-labelledby=\"checkout-modal-title\"\n      aria-describedby=\"checkout-modal-description\"\n    >\n      <button aria-label=\"Close checkout details\">\n        Close\n      </button>\n\n      <h2 id=\"checkout-modal-title\">\n        Checkout details\n      </h2>\n\n      <p id=\"checkout-modal-description\">\n        Complete the required shipping and billing details.\n      </p>\n\n      <form novalidate>\n        <div role=\"alert\" id=\"form-error-summary\">\n          Form-level submit errors appear here.\n        </div>\n\n        <fieldset>\n          <legend>Shipping information</legend>\n          ...\n        </fieldset>\n\n        <fieldset>\n          <legend>Billing information</legend>\n          ...\n        </fieldset>\n\n        <fieldset>\n          <legend>Preferences</legend>\n          ...\n        </fieldset>\n\n        <button type=\"submit\">\n          Save details\n        </button>\n\n        <button type=\"button\">\n          Cancel\n        </button>\n      </form>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</body>\n```\n\n### Semantic Requirements\n\n- The modal container uses `role=\"dialog\"` and `aria-modal=\"true\"` per APG Modal Dialog and WCAG 4.1.2.\n- The dialog must have an accessible name through `aria-labelledby` pointing to the visible modal heading. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-describedby` may point to concise explanatory text. Avoid pointing it to the entire form if the content is long, because that can create an overwhelming screen reader announcement. WCAG 1.3.1, 4.1.2.\n- The form uses native `<form>` semantics. WCAG 1.3.1.\n- Related fields are grouped with `<fieldset>` and `<legend>`, especially radio groups, checkbox groups, shipping/billing sections, and preference groups. WCAG 1.3.1, 3.3.2.\n- Each input has a visible `<label>`. Programmatic-only labels are not the default. WCAG 1.3.1, 2.4.6, 3.3.2.\n- Form instructions and errors are linked with `aria-describedby`. WCAG 1.3.1, 3.3.1, 3.3.2.\n- Background page content must not be reachable while the modal is open. Use `inert` on the app root outside the active modal where supported, with an appropriate fallback. WCAG 2.1.2, 2.4.3.\n\n---\n\n## Interaction Pattern Design\n\n### Interactive Elements Table\n\n| Widget | APG Pattern | Keyboard Model | ARIA Attributes | WCAG Citation |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Modal dialog | APG Modal Dialog: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/dialog-modal/ | Tab cycles forward inside dialog; Shift+Tab cycles backward; Escape closes active top modal | `role=\"dialog\"`, `aria-modal=\"true\"`, `aria-labelledby`, optional `aria-describedby` | 2.1.1, 2.1.2, 2.4.3, 4.1.2 |\n| Close button | APG Button: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/button/ | Tab focuses; Enter/Space activates | Native `<button>`; `aria-label` only if visible text is not sufficient | 2.1.1, 2.4.6, 4.1.2 |\n| Text inputs | Native input pattern | Tab focuses; typing edits; blur validates | `aria-invalid`, `aria-describedby`, `required` where applicable | 1.3.1, 3.3.1, 3.3.2, 4.1.2 |\n| Select controls | Native select pattern | Tab focuses; Arrow keys open/change per browser behavior | `aria-invalid`, `aria-describedby`, visible label | 1.3.1, 2.1.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Checkbox | Native checkbox pattern | Tab focuses; Space toggles | Native checked state; `aria-describedby` for hint/error | 1.3.1, 2.1.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Radio group | Native radio group pattern | Tab enters group; Arrow keys move within group; Space selects | `<fieldset>`, `<legend>`, native checked state, `aria-describedby` as needed | 1.3.1, 2.1.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Submit button | APG Button | Tab focuses; Enter/Space submits | Native `<button type=\"submit\">`; disabled state if unavailable | 2.1.1, 3.3.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Cancel button | APG Button | Tab focuses; Enter/Space closes modal | Native `<button type=\"button\">` | 2.1.1, 2.4.3, 4.1.2 |\n| Error summary links | Native links | Tab focuses; Enter moves focus to invalid field | `href=\"#field-id\"` plus programmatic focus target support | 2.1.1, 2.4.3, 3.3.1 |\n\n### Keyboard Interaction Model\n\n- `Tab`: moves to the next focusable element inside the active modal.\n- `Shift+Tab`: moves to the previous focusable element inside the active modal.\n- `Tab` on the last focusable element wraps to the first focusable element in the active modal.\n- `Shift+Tab` on the first focusable element wraps to the last focusable element in the active modal.\n- `Escape`: closes only the topmost active modal, then restores focus according to the stacked modal focus stack.\n- `Enter`: activates buttons and submits the form when focus is in a compatible form control.\n- `Space`: activates buttons and toggles checkboxes.\n- Arrow keys: preserve native behavior for radio groups and selects.\n\nDo not create custom keyboard behavior for native controls unless the native behavior is being replaced intentionally. Native controls already satisfy much of WCAG 2.1.1 and 4.1.2 when labeled and structured correctly.\n\n---\n\n## Focus Management Plan\n\n### Initial Focus\n\nWhen the modal opens:\n\n1. Store the element that opened the modal.\n2. Add the modal to a modal stack.\n3. Make background content inert or otherwise unavailable to keyboard and assistive technology.\n4. Move focus into the topmost modal.\n\nInitial focus target:\n\n- If the modal has a short form and no destructive action: focus the first meaningful form input.\n- If the modal has long explanatory content before the form: focus the modal heading with `tabindex=\"-1\"` so screen reader users hear context before entering fields.\n- If the modal represents a confirmation or potentially destructive action: focus the least destructive safe action or the heading, depending on content risk.\n\nFor this fixture, because the modal contains a multi-section form, initial focus should move to the modal heading (`h2` with `tabindex=\"-1\"`) first. This gives screen reader users the dialog title and context before the long form. WCAG 2.4.3, APG Modal Dialog.\n\n### Focus Trap\n\nThe active modal owns focus while open.\n\nFocus trap behavior:\n\n- Compute focusable elements inside the active modal only.\n- Exclude disabled, hidden, inert, `display: none`, and `visibility: hidden` elements.\n- Include enabled native controls, links with `href`, buttons, selects, textareas, and elements with non-negative `tabindex`.\n- Do not include background page elements.\n- When focus reaches the end, wrap to the beginning.\n- When focus reaches the beginning with `Shift+Tab`, wrap to the end.\n- If form validation dynamically disables or hides elements, recalculate focusable elements before each trap decision.\n\nWCAG: 2.1.1 Keyboard, 2.1.2 No Keyboard Trap, 2.4.3 Focus Order.\n\n### Focus Restoration\n\nWhen a modal closes:\n\n- If it is the topmost modal, remove it from the modal stack.\n- If another modal remains underneath, focus returns to the previously active element inside that underlying modal if it still exists and is enabled.\n- If no modal remains, focus returns to the trigger element that opened the closed modal.\n- If the trigger element no longer exists, focus should move to the nearest logical fallback, such as the button or region that replaced it, not to `<body>`.\n- Focus restoration must occur after React re-render completes.\n\nWCAG: 2.4.3 Focus Order, 2.1.2 No Keyboard Trap.\n\n### Stacked Modals\n\nStacked modal handling is required by the fixture and is high risk.\n\nRules:\n\n- Only the topmost modal is interactive.\n- Lower modals remain visually present if design requires, but must be inert to keyboard and assistive technology while covered.\n- Escape closes only the topmost modal.\n- Focus trap applies only to the topmost modal.\n- Focus restoration must use a stack, not a single global trigger reference.\n\nFailure mode to avoid: closing a child modal and sending focus back to the original page trigger while the parent modal remains open. That violates WCAG 2.4.3 and can strand screen reader users.\n\n### Focus Indicators\n\nAll focusable elements need visible focus indicators:\n\n- Use `:focus-visible`.\n- Minimum 3:1 contrast between focused and unfocused states. WCAG 2.4.7 and 2.4.13.\n- Prefer a two-color focus ring, such as dark outline plus light offset shadow, so it remains visible on different backgrounds.\n- Ensure sticky modal headers or footers do not obscure focused fields. WCAG 2.4.11.\n- At 200% zoom and narrow viewport widths, focused controls must remain visible after tabbing.\n\n---\n\n## State Communication Design\n\n### State Communication Table\n\n| State | Visual Indicator | Programmatic Indicator | ARIA Attribute | WCAG Citation |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Modal open | Overlay/backdrop, visible dialog | Dialog announced with name and modal state | `role=\"dialog\"`, `aria-modal=\"true\"`, `aria-labelledby` | 4.1.2 |\n| Modal closed | Dialog removed/hidden | Dialog removed from accessibility tree | Conditional render or `hidden`; avoid focusable hidden content | 2.4.3, 4.1.2 |\n| Background unavailable | Backdrop and inactive page | Background content inert | `inert` on app root outside modal | 2.1.2, 2.4.3 |\n| Field valid | Default border, no error text | No invalid state | Omit `aria-invalid` or set `false` | 4.1.2 |\n| Field invalid | Error text, icon, border | Invalid state exposed | `aria-invalid=\"true\"` | 3.3.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Field error message | Error text under field | Error associated with input | `aria-describedby=\"field-error-id\"` | 1.3.1, 3.3.1 |\n| Field hint | Hint text under field | Hint associated with input | `aria-describedby=\"field-hint-id\"` | 1.3.1, 3.3.2 |\n| Required field | Text marker, not color alone | Native required state | `required`, optional visible \u201crequired\u201d text | 1.3.1, 3.3.2 |\n| Disabled control | Muted appearance, unavailable cursor | Native disabled state | `disabled` for native controls; `aria-disabled` only for custom widgets | 4.1.2 |\n| Submit loading | Spinner plus \u201cSaving\u2026\u201d text | Busy/status state | `aria-busy=\"true\"` on form region; `role=\"status\"` for status text | 4.1.3 |\n| Submit error | Error summary at top of form | Assertive announcement | `role=\"alert\"` on summary or assertive live region | 3.3.1, 4.1.3 |\n| Successful submit | Success message or modal close | Polite status if modal remains open | `role=\"status\"` | 4.1.3 |\n\n### Validation Behavior\n\nOn blur:\n\n- Validate the field.\n- If invalid, display an error message near the field.\n- Set `aria-invalid=\"true\"` on the input.\n- Add or update `aria-describedby` so it references both hint text and error text where both exist.\n- Do not create one live region per field. Use field association for field-level feedback.\n- Avoid assertive live announcements for every blur error; that can become noisy.\n\nOn submit:\n\n- Validate all fields.\n- If errors exist, show an error summary at the top of the form.\n- Move focus to the error summary, or to the first invalid field if the form is short. For this complex multi-section form, focus the error summary first.\n- Error summary should list each error as a link that moves focus to the corresponding invalid field.\n- Use `role=\"alert\"` or an assertive live region for the submit failure summary. WCAG 4.1.3.\n- Preserve user-entered values. WCAG 3.3.7 Redundant Entry.\n\nError messages must be specific:\n\n- Good: \u201cEmail address is missing.\u201d\n- Good: \u201cZIP code must contain 5 digits.\u201d\n- Bad: \u201cInvalid input.\u201d\n\nWCAG: 3.3.1 Error Identification, 3.3.2 Labels or Instructions, 3.3.3 Error Suggestion where applicable.\n\n---\n\n## Visual Accessibility Plan\n\n- Normal text must meet 4.5:1 contrast. WCAG 1.4.3.\n- Large text must meet 3:1 contrast. WCAG 1.4.3.\n- Form borders, focus rings, icons, checkmarks, and selected states must meet 3:1 non-text contrast. WCAG 1.4.11.\n- Error state must not rely on red alone. Use red border + error icon + visible error text. WCAG 1.4.1.\n- Required fields must not rely only on color or an asterisk without explanation. Provide visible \u201crequired\u201d text or a clear legend explaining the marker. WCAG 1.4.1, 3.3.2.\n- Modal close, submit, cancel, checkbox, radio, and select targets must be at least 24x24 CSS pixels, with 44x44 preferred for touch. WCAG 2.5.8.\n- The modal must reflow at 320px CSS width equivalent without horizontal scrolling. WCAG 1.4.10.\n- The modal must support 200% zoom without clipping focused fields or action buttons. WCAG 1.4.4, 1.4.10.\n- If the modal body scrolls, the header/footer layout must not hide the currently focused element. WCAG 2.4.11.\n- Motion must respect `prefers-reduced-motion`. Modal open/close animations should be removed or reduced. WCAG 2.3.3.\n- Body text links inside form descriptions must be underlined or otherwise distinguishable by more than color. WCAG 1.4.1.\n\n---\n\n## Content Accessibility Plan\n\n- Modal title must be visible and referenced by `aria-labelledby`. WCAG 2.4.6, 4.1.2.\n- Close button must have a clear accessible name. If the visible label is only an icon, the button needs `aria-label=\"Close checkout details\"`. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- Decorative icons, including close \u201c\u00d7\u201d, error icons, and spinner graphics, must be hidden with `aria-hidden=\"true\"` when text already communicates meaning. WCAG 1.1.1, 4.1.2.\n- Every field needs a visible label. WCAG 1.3.1, 3.3.2.\n- Fieldsets and legends must describe grouped controls, especially radio and checkbox groups. WCAG 1.3.1.\n- Hints must be concise and linked with `aria-describedby`. WCAG 3.3.2.\n- Error messages must identify the problem and, when possible, suggest a correction. WCAG 3.3.1, 3.3.3.\n- DOM order must match visual reading and tab order. WCAG 1.3.2, 2.4.3.\n- If the modal includes product images or icons, decorative images use empty alt; informative images receive concise alt text. WCAG 1.1.1.\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n### Automated Testing\n\nUse axe-core runtime scans for:\n\n- Dialog accessible name.\n- Valid ARIA attributes.\n- Missing labels.\n- Error association where detectable.\n- Color contrast.\n- Landmark and heading issues.\n- Hidden focusable content where detectable.\n\nAxe will not fully prove focus trapping, focus restoration, Escape behavior, or live region announcement quality. Those need keyboard and screen reader testing.\n\n### DOM Verification\n\nRequired DOM checks:\n\n- Active dialog has `role=\"dialog\"`.\n- Active dialog has `aria-modal=\"true\"`.\n- Active dialog has `aria-labelledby` pointing to an existing visible heading.\n- Background app root is inert or otherwise not focusable.\n- Invalid fields receive `aria-invalid=\"true\"`.\n- Error messages have stable IDs.\n- Invalid fields\u2019 `aria-describedby` includes the corresponding error ID.\n- Hidden/closed dialogs do not contain tabbable elements.\n- Only the topmost stacked modal is tabbable.\n\n### Keyboard Test Cases\n\n- Open modal from trigger button; focus moves to modal heading or first planned focus target.\n- Press Tab repeatedly; focus cycles through modal controls and never reaches background page.\n- Press Shift+Tab repeatedly; focus cycles backward through modal controls.\n- Press Escape; topmost modal closes.\n- After Escape closes final modal, focus returns to original trigger button.\n- Open parent modal, then child modal; focus moves to child modal.\n- Press Escape in child modal; only child closes and focus returns to parent modal context.\n- Press Escape in parent modal; parent closes and focus returns to page trigger.\n- Submit with invalid fields; focus moves to error summary.\n- Activate an error summary link; focus moves to the corresponding invalid field.\n- Tab at 200% zoom; focused elements remain visible and unobscured.\n\n### Screen Reader Test Scenarios\n\nTest with NVDA, JAWS, and VoiceOver:\n\n- On open, screen reader announces dialog title and modal context.\n- User can navigate headings and form sections inside the modal.\n- Field labels, legends, hints, and errors are announced correctly.\n- Invalid fields announce their error text through description association.\n- Submit error summary is announced.\n- Background page content is not reachable while modal is open.\n- Closing the modal returns the screen reader\u2019s virtual and keyboard context to the trigger area.\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n\nThe implementation is acceptable when:\n\n- The modal follows APG Modal Dialog semantics and keyboard behavior.\n- Focus cannot escape the topmost modal while it is open.\n- Focus restoration works for single and stacked modal scenarios.\n- Escape closes only the topmost modal.\n- Every field has a visible label.\n- Grouped controls use fieldset/legend.\n- Validation errors are visible, specific, and programmatically associated.\n- Submit failure is announced.\n- Focus indicators are visible and meet contrast requirements.\n- DOM verification confirms ARIA attributes are present on the correct elements.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Tasks\n\n### Task 1: Reusable Modal Shell\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint after this task**\n\n**Files:**\n\n- Reusable modal component\n- Modal stack/focus manager\n- Modal tests\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n\n```html\n<div class=\"modal-layer\">\n  <div class=\"modal-backdrop\"></div>\n  <div\n    role=\"dialog\"\n    aria-modal=\"true\"\n    aria-labelledby=\"modal-title-id\"\n    aria-describedby=\"modal-description-id\"\n  >\n    <button aria-label=\"Close [dialog name]\">...</button>\n    <h2 id=\"modal-title-id\" tabindex=\"-1\">...</h2>\n    <p id=\"modal-description-id\">...</p>\n    ...\n  </div>\n</div>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n\n- `role=\"dialog\"`: exposes dialog role. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-modal=\"true\"`: communicates modal behavior. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-labelledby`: gives dialog accessible name. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-describedby`: gives concise supporting context. WCAG 1.3.1, 4.1.2.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n\n- Tab and Shift+Tab remain inside active modal.\n- Escape closes topmost modal.\n- Enter/Space activate buttons.\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Dialog has accessible name.\n- Initial focus moves into modal.\n- Focus trap works forward and backward.\n- Escape closes modal.\n- Background content is not tabbable.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n\n- 2.1.1 Keyboard\n- 2.1.2 No Keyboard Trap\n- 2.4.3 Focus Order\n- 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value\n\n---\n\n### Task 2: Focus Restoration and Stacked Modal Manager\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint after this task**\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n\n```text\nModal stack:\n- trigger element reference\n- active modal element reference\n- previous focused element inside parent modal\n- restore target fallback\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n\n- No new ARIA required beyond active dialog semantics.\n- Background and lower modal inert behavior must be reflected in rendered DOM. WCAG 2.1.2, 2.4.3.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n\n- Escape closes only topmost modal.\n- Tab trap applies only to topmost modal.\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Close single modal restores focus to trigger.\n- Close child modal restores focus to parent modal context.\n- Close parent modal restores focus to page trigger.\n- Removed trigger uses logical fallback.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n\n- 2.1.2 No Keyboard Trap\n- 2.4.3 Focus Order\n- 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value\n\n---\n\n### Task 3: Multi-Section Form Structure\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint after this task**\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n\n```html\n<form novalidate>\n  <fieldset>\n    <legend>Shipping information</legend>\n\n    <label for=\"shipping-name\">Full name</label>\n    <input\n      id=\"shipping-name\"\n      name=\"shippingName\"\n      autocomplete=\"name\"\n      required\n      aria-describedby=\"shipping-name-hint shipping-name-error\"\n    />\n\n    <p id=\"shipping-name-hint\">Enter the name for delivery.</p>\n    <p id=\"shipping-name-error\">Full name is required.</p>\n  </fieldset>\n\n  <fieldset>\n    <legend>Delivery preferences</legend>\n    ...\n  </fieldset>\n</form>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n\n- `aria-describedby`: links hints and errors. WCAG 1.3.1, 3.3.2.\n- `aria-invalid`: marks invalid fields. WCAG 3.3.1, 4.1.2.\n- `required`: communicates required native input state. WCAG 1.3.1, 3.3.2.\n- Native checked/selected states for checkbox, radio, and select controls. WCAG 4.1.2.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n\n- Tab follows DOM order through sections.\n- Radio groups use native arrow key behavior.\n- Space toggles checkboxes.\n- Enter submits when appropriate.\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Every input has a visible label.\n- Every grouped input has a fieldset/legend.\n- Tab order follows visual order.\n- Radio and checkbox controls operate with keyboard.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n\n- 1.3.1 Info and Relationships\n- 1.3.2 Meaningful Sequence\n- 2.1.1 Keyboard\n- 2.4.3 Focus Order\n- 3.3.2 Labels or Instructions\n- 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value\n\n---\n\n### Task 4: Validation and Error Recovery\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint after this task**\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n\n```html\n<div id=\"form-error-summary\" role=\"alert\" tabindex=\"-1\">\n  <h3>There are 3 errors in this form</h3>\n  <ul>\n    <li><a href=\"#shipping-name\">Full name is required.</a></li>\n  </ul>\n</div>\n\n<input\n  id=\"shipping-name\"\n  aria-invalid=\"true\"\n  aria-describedby=\"shipping-name-hint shipping-name-error\"\n/>\n\n<p id=\"shipping-name-error\">\n  Full name is required.\n</p>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n\n- `role=\"alert\"` for submit-level error summary. WCAG 4.1.3.\n- `aria-invalid=\"true\"` on invalid fields. WCAG 3.3.1, 4.1.2.\n- `aria-describedby` linking field to error. WCAG 1.3.1.\n- `tabindex=\"-1\"` on error summary to allow programmatic focus. WCAG 2.4.3.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n\n- Submit with errors moves focus to summary.\n- Error summary links move focus to fields.\n- Field-level correction clears invalid state when valid.\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Blur validation associates field error.\n- Submit validation focuses error summary.\n- Error summary links focus invalid fields.\n- No repeated per-field assertive live regions are created.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n\n- 1.3.1 Info and Relationships\n- 2.4.3 Focus Order\n- 3.3.1 Error Identification\n- 3.3.2 Labels or Instructions\n- 3.3.3 Error Suggestion\n- 4.1.3 Status Messages\n\n---\n\n### Task 5: Visual Focus and Responsive Modal Behavior\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint after this task**\n\n**Requirements:**\n\n- Two-color `:focus-visible` indicator.\n- At least 3:1 contrast for focus indicator.\n- Touch targets at least 24x24 CSS px, preferably 44x44.\n- Modal content scrolls without trapping keyboard users in hidden areas.\n- Sticky modal header/footer must not obscure focused controls.\n- Reduced motion removes or simplifies modal animations.\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Screenshot focus states.\n- Test keyboard navigation at 200% zoom.\n- Test narrow viewport reflow.\n- Test reduced-motion setting.\n- Test high contrast mode where available.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n\n- 1.4.1 Use of Color\n- 1.4.3 Contrast Minimum\n- 1.4.10 Reflow\n- 1.4.11 Non-text Contrast\n- 2.3.3 Animation from Interactions\n- 2.4.7 Focus Visible\n- 2.4.11 Focus Not Obscured\n- 2.4.13 Focus Appearance\n- 2.5.8 Target Size\n\n---\n\n## a11y-Critic Review Checkpoints\n\n| Checkpoint | After Task | Focus Areas |\n|---|---|---|\n| \ud83d\udd0d 1 | Modal Shell | APG Dialog semantics, accessible name, initial focus, background inertness |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 2 | Focus Manager | Forward/backward trap, Escape handling, stacked modal restoration |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 3 | Form Structure | Labels, fieldsets, legends, DOM order, native controls |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 4 | Validation | Error summary, `aria-invalid`, `aria-describedby`, live region strategy |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 5 | Visual Accessibility | Focus indicators, zoom, reflow, touch targets, reduced motion |\n\n---\n\n## Failure Modes This Plan Prevents\n\n- Dialog has `role=\"dialog\"` but no accessible name.\n- Focus moves behind the modal.\n- Shift+Tab escapes the modal.\n- Escape closes both parent and child stacked modals.\n- Focus restores to the wrong trigger.\n- Hidden modal controls remain tabbable.\n- Errors are shown visually but not associated with fields.\n- One assertive live region is rendered per field in a loop.\n- Radio and checkbox groups lack fieldset/legend.\n- Required/error states rely on color alone.\n- Focus indicator is hidden by modal sticky footer.\n- Submit error summary appears but keyboard focus stays on submit button.\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n- WAI-ARIA APG Modal Dialog Pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/dialog-modal/\n- WAI-ARIA APG Button Pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/button/\n- WCAG 2.2 Quick Reference: https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG22/quickref/\n- WCAG 2.1.1 Keyboard\n- WCAG 2.1.2 No Keyboard Trap\n- WCAG 2.4.3 Focus Order\n- WCAG 2.4.7 Focus Visible\n- WCAG 2.4.11 Focus Not Obscured\n- WCAG 2.4.13 Focus Appearance\n- WCAG 3.3.1 Error Identification\n- WCAG 3.3.2 Labels or Instructions\n- WCAG 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value\n- WCAG 4.1.3 Status Messages",
  "done": true,
